    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_984483420" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/984483420" />
    <a title="Tom Bensley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4716829-tom-bensley"><img alt="Tom Bensley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609757098p2/4716829.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/984483420?book_show_action=true">Jul 02, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Bensley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Bensley" href="/user/show/4716829-tom-bensley">Tom Bensley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4716829-tom-bensley?shelf=help-me-write-please">help-me-write-please</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer984483420" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17566769859366212469"><b>The Letters of Flannery O’Connor (The Habit of Being)</b><br/><br/>I thought about writing a traditional review, where I ramble on about how I felt about this and that in the book and try and find a consistent point to all my thoughts, but I won’t do that this time. An author’s correspondence covers such a wide range of topics and themes and tells so many stories (and is always a bit mysterious when you don’t get the respondent’s letters) that it’s difficult to write a review that it covers it, and it usually</span>
  <span id="freeText17566769859366212469" style="display:none"><b>The Letters of Flannery O’Connor (The Habit of Being)</b><br /><br />I thought about writing a traditional review, where I ramble on about how I felt about this and that in the book and try and find a consistent point to all my thoughts, but I won’t do that this time. An author’s correspondence covers such a wide range of topics and themes and tells so many stories (and is always a bit mysterious when you don’t get the respondent’s letters) that it’s difficult to write a review that it covers it, and it usually just ends up being vague praise and a recommendation to read the thing. Well, I’ll go you one better (maybe). I couldn’t begin to sing my praises of Flannery O’Connor’s talents and how important her writing is to me (if I did it would be a long, loud ballad about my university days, and I’m no singer) so I’ve just compiled a few of my favourite quotes under appropriate headings. These quotes reflect the strange, compelling and brilliant mind of Flannery O’Connor, one that was devoted to craft and religion and undeterred (in fact, inspired) by a relentless bout of lupus (and some rheumatism thrown in for good measure) that eventually killed her. O’Connor’s humour is one of a kind and if you happen to get it, you’ll find in her a kindred spirit and an entertaining storyteller to boot.<br /> <br />(Quotes collected from the Library of America edition)<br /><br /><b>On writing</b><br /><br />(O’Connor’s writing advice is just like her writing: Straight to the point, no-nonsense and if you don’t like it, she won’t bother to defend it.)<br /><br />“The effort to maintain a tone is a considerable strain, particularly as I never know exactly what tone I am maintaining.” (918)<br /><br />“When you start describing the significance of a symbol like the tunnel which recurs in [Wise Blood], you immediately begin to limit it and a symbol should go on deepening.” (924).<br /><br />“To have sympathy for any character you have to put a good deal of yourself in him.” (956).<br /><br />“Few poets have any business to write novels.” (960).<br /><br />“I have always insisted there is a fine grain of stupidity in the fiction writer.” (990).<br /><br />“… the writer doesn’t have to understand, only reproduce. And what makes him reproduce is not having the experience but contemplating the experience and contemplating it don’t mean understanding it so much as understanding that he doesn’t understand it.” (1007).<br /><br />“… it is never wise to decide beforehand what length a thing will be. It will be as long as it takes to do it.” (1017).<br /><br />“A story is never a study if it is any good.” (1029).<br /> <br />“All my stories are about the action of grace on a character who is not very willing to support it.” (1067)<br /><br />“I thought a bloody semicolon was for a long pause. What is it for?” (1138).<br /><br /><b>On illness</b><br /><br />(O’Connor had lupus (of which she died at 40) and hobbled around on crutches due to rheumatism in her hip. But in these letters she’s so upbeat, so funny and would rather be “drawn and quartered” than complain about her situation, that her updates on the condition of her health are, at times, a grotesque joy to read.)<br /><br />“I am learning to walk on crutches and I feel like a large stiff anthropoid ape who has no cause to be thinking of St. Thomas or Aristotle.” (956)<br /><br />“It requires some decision for me at this point to cross the room, much less the ocean.” (on travelling) (961).<br /><br />“I can’t even kneel down to say my prayers.” (1028).<br /><br />“My father died of the same stuff at the age of 44 but the scientists hope to keep me here until I am 96. I owe my existence and cheerful countenance to the pituitary glands of thousands of pigs butchered daily in Chicago Illinois at the Armour packing plant.” (1063).<br /><br />“I am strapped up with a broken rib, of all things. I broke it coughing.” (1083). <br /><br />“When the grim reaper comes to get me, he’ll have to give me a few extra hours to revise my final words. No end to this.” (1090).<br /><br /><b>On faith/God</b><br /><br />(If you’ve read her fiction, her faith will already be apparent to you. The letters show O’Connor’s dogmatic defence of the Church and Catholicism and the Bible’s teachings, but she has these beliefs for herself. She only sermonises in letters when her correspondents ask her to, otherwise she is content that others believe what they believe, because this is the way things are.)<br /><br />“… I see everything as beginning with original sin, taking in the Redemption, and reckoning on a final judgement.” (930)<br /><br />“I didn’t mean to suggest that science is unreliable but only that we can’t judge God by the limits of our knowledge of natural things.” (954)<br /><br />“I have a one-legged friend and I asked her what they said to John at the gate. She reckoned they said, “The lame shall enter first.” This may be because the lame will be able to knock everybody aside with their crutches.” (969).<br /><br />“…when all you see will be God, all you will want will be God.” (976).<br /><br />“What kept me a sceptic in college was precisely my Christian faith. It always said: wait don’t bite on this, get a wider picture, continue to read.” (1165).<br /><br /><b>On Georgia/Milledgeville</b><br /><br />“The following is good Georgia advice: don’t marry no foreigner. Even if his face is white, his heart is black.” (1027).<br /><br />“Greetings from historic Milledgeville where the ladies and gents wash in separate tubs.” (1032)<br /><br /><b>Her mother</b><br /><br />(If there is a secondary character in this collection, it’s O’Connor’s mother. They live together in isolation on their farm in Milledgeville Georgia (plus 30 or so birds) and the brief snapshots of their interactions O’Connor puts in her letters are odd-couple gold.)<br /><br />SHE: “Mobby Dick. I’ve always heard about that.”<br />ME: “Mow-by Dick.”<br />SHE: “MOW-by Dick. The Idiot. You would get something called The Idiot. What’s it about?”<br />ME: “An idiot.” (908)<br /><br />“My mama is thinking about getting a Hungarian family.” (1009).<br /><br />“I think the reason I am a short story writer is so my mother can read my work in one sitting.” (1100).<br /><br /><b>On the Beat writers</b><br /><br />“That seems about the most appalling thing you could do—read them.” (1098).<br /><br />“Certainly some revolt against our exaggerated materialism is long overdue. They seem to know a good many of the right things to run away from but to lack any necessary discipline. They call themselves holy but holiness costs and so far as I can see they pay nothing.”<br /><br />“You can’t trust them as poets because they’re too busy acting like poets. The true poet is anonymous … but these boys have to look, act and apparently smell like poets.”<br /><br /><b>On fame</b><br /><br />(That which that gets in the way of one’s writing business.)<br /><br />“I wish somebody intelligent would write me sometime but I seem to attract the lunatic fringe mainly.” (935).<br /><br />“Success is almost as isolating [as illness] and nothing points out vanity as well.”<br /><br />“At Emory they had a list of questions for me to answer and the first one was: Do you write from imagination or experience? My inclination at such a point is always to get deathly stupid and say, ‘Ah jus writes.’” (1022 – 23)<br /><br /><b>On everything else</b><br /><br />(Some things just have to be put into O’Connor’s perspective. She likes to say how little she knows (so did Socrates) and how she’s no good judge on a piece of literature or anything intellectual, but this is all just good old-fashioned Southern modesty. Her turns of phrase and her anecdotes show she was a person who knew how things ought to be, even if nobody else agreed. God bless you, Mary Flannery O’Connor, and rest in peace. I love you and I always will.)<br /><br />“Do you read the National Geographic or do you smell it? I smell it … If Time smelt like the Nat’l Geo. there would be some excuse for its being printed.” (998).<br /><br />“I feel that since I have now reached the lunatic fringe there is no place left for me to go.” (916)<br /><br />“I have not been helped or hurt by my education, only kind of haunted.” (922).<br /><br />“As for lesbianism I regard that as any other form of uncleanness.” (925).<br /><br />“Never lend a book to a man as you will have to set a stick of dynamite under him before you get it back.” (1012).<br /> <br />“I hope you understand that it is not the tooth of the sabor-toothed [sp] tiger I want, it is the tiger. I don’t care if it’s an old toothless tiger or not, just so it’s alive. I intend to start a zoo.” (1033).<br /> <br />“I am not interested in normal psychology.” (1148).</span>
  <a data-text-id="17566769859366212469" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


