<div id="review_3570560147" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3570560147" />
    <a title="Paul Jellinek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2942842-paul-jellinek"><img alt="Paul Jellinek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298389715p2/2942842.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3570560147?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul Jellinek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul Jellinek" href="/user/show/2942842-paul-jellinek">Paul Jellinek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3570560147" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15244817602603583960">What a wonderful book! Flannery O&apos;Connor, a Catholic author who lived with her mother and her peacocks in Milledgeville, Georgia, and died of lupus while still in her 30&apos;s, was one the great American writers of the 20th century. After reading her two novels and her two collections of short stories in the Library of America edition of her work, I&apos;d read a selection of her letters (also included in the LOA edition), but I wanted more--and that&apos;s what I got in this superb collection, compiled and e</span>
  <span id="freeText15244817602603583960" style="display:none">What a wonderful book! Flannery O'Connor, a Catholic author who lived with her mother and her peacocks in Milledgeville, Georgia, and died of lupus while still in her 30's, was one the great American writers of the 20th century. After reading her two novels and her two collections of short stories in the Library of America edition of her work, I'd read a selection of her letters (also included in the LOA edition), but I wanted more--and that's what I got in this superb collection, compiled and edited by her longtime friend Sally Fitzgerald: almost 600 pages of some of the greatest letters I've ever read anywhere, by anyone. They are in turn ruthlessly honest, brilliantly insightful, and often screamingly funny, and together they provide an indelible portrait of this remarkable artist. If you've already read some of her books, these letters will give you rich new insights into those works; if you haven't, you'll be running to your bookstore as soon as you've finished reading these letters.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15244817602603583960" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


